I have a fixed position `&lt;div&gt;` with the following CSS declarations applied

    width: 100vw;
    height: 100vw;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    overflow: scroll;

Now imagine that the `&lt;div&gt;` has a few paragraphs of text within it, forcing the user to scroll when browsing from a mobile device.

When scrolling through the  `&lt;div&gt;` in iOS Safari the scroll feels quite laboured and slow. This is in comparison to having the content directly in the statically positioned body.

My question is: why does iOS Safari feel slow and laboured when scrolling a an element that has the position set to fixed and overflow set to scroll?

My next question is; is there a way to work around this so that the scroll feels as smooth as it would if the element was static or relative and had visible overflow applied.

