I think this is a nice way to prevent a callback function that is passed from Parent to cause a re render of the child. 

[Here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58158932/1641941) is more complicated example of how to prevent items from re rendering because the callback function changed reference. 

Creating a new reference for handlers like onClick are even worse because a dom render will take place since React will fail to see shadow doms are equal after a deep compare. However; for Parent to be able to modify the list, the list has to be available in it&#39;s closure so after changing the list the onClick callback has to change (new closure to the list).

Lets investigate how useEventCallback solves this:

    function useEventCallback(fn) {
      //ref will never change during component life cycle
      const ref = React.useRef();

      //every time useEventCallback is called we set ref.current again.
      //  we can add fn as a dependency but if you see how Parent calls it
      //  it will have the same outcome because useEventCallback(()=&gt;...)
      //  causes fn to be different every time anyway
      useEffect(() =&gt; {
        ref.current = fn;
      });
      //here we return a function that will never change during the component
      //  life cycle but what it does will change during it&#39;s life cycle
      //  because we keep mutating ref and resetting ref.current
      return React.useCallback(
        (...args) =&gt; ref.current.apply(void 0, args),
        []//you can do [ref] here but linter knows ref will never change so no needfor it
      );
    }

We see that no matter how many times we call `useEventCallback` during a component life cycle the returned value will never change (never change reference, the implementation will change because we mutate ref and reset the callback)

Here is a full example:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: true --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function useEventCallback(callback) {
      //ref will never change during component life cycle
      const ref = React.useRef();

      //every time useEventCallback is called we set ref.current again.
      //  we can add fn as a dependency but if you see how Parent calls it
      //  it will have the same outcome because useEventCallback(()=&gt;...)
      //  causes fn to be different every time anyway
      React.useEffect(() =&gt; {
        ref.current = callback;
      });
      //here we return a function that will never change during the component
      //  life cycle but what it does will change during it&#39;s life cycle
      //  because we keep mutating ref and resetting ref.current
      return React.useCallback(
        (...args) =&gt; ref.current.apply(void 0, args),
        []
      );
    }

    const ParentContainer = () =&gt; {
      //list is created and maintained in parent
      const [list, setList] = React.useState([
        { id: 1, val: true },
        { id: 2, val: true },
      ]);
      //toggle will keep the same reference every re render
      //  (when list changes) so lastRender toggle === current render toggle
      //  but because calling useEventCallback mutates the ref
      //  the implementation will change, best of both worlds
      //  toggle stays the same during component life cycle so Items
      //  will not needlessly render but the list that is used in closure
      //  will change every time we call useEventCallback
      const toggle = useEventCallback(id =&gt;
        setList(
          list.map(item =&gt;
            item.id === id ? { ...item, val: !item.val } : item
          )
        )
      );
      return Parent({ list, toggle });
    };
    const Parent = ({ list, toggle }) =&gt; (
      &lt;div&gt;
        {list.map(item =&gt; (
          &lt;ItemContainer
            key={item.id}
            item={item}
            //every item gets the same toggle function
            //  reference to toggle never changes during Parent life cycle
            toggle={toggle}
          /&gt;
        ))}
      &lt;/div&gt;
    );
    //Added memo to make ItemContainer a pure component
    //  as long as item or toggle never changes the (render) function
    //  will not be executed
    //  normally a pure component should not have side effects so don&#39;t
    //  do side effects in pure compnents (like mutating rendered var)
